public class Introduction {
    public static void introductionToTheGame() {
        System.out.println(" ");
        System.out.println("Introduction:");

        System.out.println("Monopoly is a multi-player economics-themed board game. In the game, players roll two dice to move around the game board, buying and trading properties and developing them \nwith houses and hotels. " +
                "Players collect rent from their opponents, aiming to drive them into bankruptcy. Money can also be gained or lost through Chance and Community Chest \ncards and tax squares.Players receive a stipend every time they pass Go and can end up in jail, from which they cannot move until they have met one of three conditions." +
                "\nHouse rules, hundreds of different editions, many spin-offs, and related media exist.");

        System.out.println(" ");
        System.out.println("Equipment:");

        System.out.println(" ");
        System.out.println("Cards:");
        System.out.println("A deck of thirty-two Chance and Community Chest cards (sixteen each) which players draw when they land on the corresponding squares of the track,\nand follow the instructions printed on them.");

        System.out.println(" ");
        System.out.println("Deeds:");
        System.out.println("A title deed for each property is given to a player to signify ownership, and specifies purchase price, mortgage value, the cost of building houses and hotels on that property, \nand the various rents depending on how developed the property is. Properties include: \n-Four railroads, players collect $25 rent if they own one railroad; $50 for two; $100 for three; $200 for all four. \nThese are usually replaced by railroad stations in non-U.S. editions of Monopoly. \n-Twenty-two cities divided into eight color groups of two or three cities; a player must own all of a color group to build houses or hotels. \n-Two utilities, rent is four times the dice value if one utility is owned, but ten times if both are owned. Hotels and houses cannot be built on utilities or stations.");

        System.out.println(" ");
        System.out.println("Dice:");
        System.out.println("2 standard dice");

        System.out.println(" ");
        System.out.println("Houses and hotels:");
        System.out.println("32 houses and 12 hotels made of wood or plastic. Unlike money, houses and hotels have a finite supply. If no more are available, no substitute is allowed.");

        System.out.println(" ");
        System.out.println("Money:");
        System.out.println("-20 $500 bills \n" +
                "-20 $100 bills \n" +
                "-30 $50 bills \n" +
                "-50 $20 bills \n" +
                "-40 $10 bills \n" +
                "-40 $5 bills \n" +
                "-40 $1 bills");

        System.out.println(" ");
        System.out.println("Official rules:");
        System.out.println("Each player starts with $1,500 in their bank. Players take turns in order, with the initial player determined by chance before the game. \nA typical turn begins with the dice rolling and advancing a piece clockwise around the board the corresponding number of squares. If players roll doubles, \nthey move again after completing that portion of their turn. A player who rolls three consecutive sets of doubles on one turn has been caught speeding and is immediately sent to \njail instead of moving the amount shown on the dice for the third roll.");
        System.out.println("A player who lands on or passes the 'Go' space collects $200 from the bank. Players who land on either Income Tax or Luxury Tax pay the \nindicated amount to the bank. In older editions of the game, two options were given for Income Tax: either pay a flat fee of $200 or 10% of total net worth \n(including the current values of all the properties and buildings owned). \nNo calculation could be made before the choice, and no latitude was given for reversing an unwise decision. In 2008, the calculation option was removed from the official rules; \nsimultaneously, the Luxury Tax was increased from $75 to $100. No reward or penalty is given for landing on Free Parking.");
        System.out.println("Properties can only be developed once a player owns all the properties in that color group. They then must be developed equally. \nA house must be built on each property of that color before a second can be built. Each property within a group must be within one house level of all the others within that group.");

        System.out.println(" ");
        System.out.println("Chance/Community Chest:");
        System.out.println("If a player lands on a Chance or Community Chest space, they draw the top card from the respective deck and follow its instructions. \nThis may include collecting or paying money to the bank or another player or moving to a different space on the board. ");

        System.out.println(" ");
        System.out.println("Jail:");
        System.out.println("A player is sent to jail for doing any of the following:\n" +
                "Landing directly on the Go to Jail space \n" +
                "Throwing three consecutive doubles in one turn \n" +
                "Drawing a Go (Directly) to Jail card from Chance or Community Chest");
        System.out.println("When a player is sent to Jail, they move directly to the 'In Jail' part of the 'In Jail/Just Visiting' space, and their turn ends ('Do not pass Go. Do not collect $200.'). \nIf an ordinary dice roll (not one of the above events) ends with the player's token on the Jail corner, they are Just Visiting and can move ahead on their next turn without penalty");
        System.out.println("If a player is in Jail, they do not take a normal turn and must either pay a fine of $50 to be released, use a Chance or Community Chest Get Out of Jail Free card, or attempt to roll doubles on the dice. \nIf a player fails to roll doubles, they lose their turn. Failing to roll doubles for three consecutive turns requires the player to either pay the $50 fine or use a Get Out of Jail Free card, after which they move ahead according to the total rolled. \nPlayers in Jail may not buy properties directly from the bank since they cannot move. This does not impede any other transaction, meaning they can engage in, for example, mortgaging properties, selling/trading properties to other players, buying/selling houses and hotels, collecting rent, and bidding on property auctions. A player who rolls doubles to leave jail does not roll again; however, if the player pays the fine or uses a card to get out and then rolls doubles, they take another turn.");

        System.out.println(" ");
        System.out.println("Properties:");
        System.out.println("If the player lands on an unowned property, whether street, railroad, or utility, they can buy the property for its listed purchase price. \nIf they decline this purchase, the property is auctioned off by the bank to the highest bidder, including the player who declined to buy.If the property landed on \nis already owned and unmortgaged, they must pay the owner a given rent; the amount depends on whether the property is part of a set or its level of development. \nPlayers may trade properties or sell them to other players at any time in any deal that is mutually agreed upon, with the exception that properties with buildings may \nnot be traded or sold. When a player owns all the properties in a color group and none of them are mortgaged, they may develop them during their turn or in between other \nplayer's turns. Development involves buying miniature houses or hotels from the bank and placing them on the property spaces; this must be done uniformly across the group. \nTherefore, a second house cannot be built on any property within a group until all of them have one house. Once the player owns an entire group, they can collect double rent \nfor any undeveloped properties within it. Although houses and hotels cannot be built on railroads or utilities, the given rent increases if a player owns more than one of \neither type. If there is a housing shortage (more demand for houses to be built than what remains in the bank), then a housing auction is conducted to determine who will get to purchase each house.");

        System.out.println(" ");
        System.out.println("Mortgaging:");
        System.out.println("Properties can also be mortgaged, although all developments on a monopoly must be sold before any property of that color can be mortgaged or traded. \nThe player receives half the purchase price from the bank for each mortgaged property. This must be repaid with 10% interest to clear the mortgage. Houses and hotels can be sold back to the bank for half their purchase price. \nPlayers cannot collect rent on mortgaged properties and may not give improved property away to others; however, trading mortgaged properties is allowed. The player receiving the mortgaged property must immediately pay the bank the mortgage price plus 10% or pay just the 10% amount and \nkeep the property mortgaged;if the player chooses the latter, they must pay the 10% again when they pay off the mortgage.");

        System.out.println(" ");
        System.out.println("Bankruptcy:");
        System.out.println("A player who cannot pay what they owe is bankrupt and eliminated from the game. If the bankrupt player owes the bank, they must turn all their \nassets over to the bank, who then auctions off their properties (if they have any), except buildings. If the debt is owed to another player instead, all assets are given to that opponent, except buildings, which must be returned to the bank. The new owner must either pay off any mortgages held by the bank on such properties received or pay a fee of 10% of the mortgaged value to the bank if they choose to leave the properties mortgaged.");
        System.out.println("The winner is the player remaining after all of the others have gone bankrupt. In a 2-player game, if a player goes bankrupt to the other player or the bank, \nthe game is over and there is no need for the bank to conduct the auction as the other player will have automatically won. The winning player only then needs to pay the final fees from the property transfer, in the event of a tournament where each dollar in net assets actually matters.");
        System.out.println("If a player runs out of money but still has assets that can be converted to cash, they can do so by selling buildings, mortgaging properties, \nor trading with other players. To avoid bankruptcy the player must be able to raise enough cash to pay the full amount owed.");
        System.out.println("A player cannot choose to go bankrupt; if there is no way to pay what they owe, even by returning all their buildings at a loss, mortgaging all \ntheir real estate and giving up all their cash, even knowing they are likely going bankrupt the next time, they must do so and immediately retire from the game.");

        System.out.println(" ");
        System.out.println("Each Monopoly player begins with $1,500.");
        System.out.println("2 X $500, 2 X $100, 2 X $50, 6 X $20, and 5 each of $10, $5, $1.");

        System.out.println(" ");
        System.out.println("The game can play:2-6 players");
        System.out.println(" ");
        System.out.println("Press 'Enter' to continue");
    }
}
